De Gen. ad lit. 6: 3 adds suum after patrem, and also reads coniungetur uxori suae,· but elsewhere in the same work as in 8: 5; 9: 19 the verb used is adhaerebit. De Gen. con. Man. 2:13 also reads adhaerebit, perhaps influenced by Ephes. 5: 31, 32, which is quoted in the same place. Con. duas epist. Pelag. 1: 5 reads patrem suum et matrem suam. So also in Speculum Mark, which also reads adhaerebit ad uxorem suam. The last clause of the verse very frequently quoted. 2 5. Confundebantur is the verb universally found except in De Gen. ad lit. Many adaptations of the verse appear. Cf. De Nupt. et Con. 1:53 De civ. 14:17; Con. Jul. 14:16, et al.

CHAPTER 3

1. Loc. 138. Same as De Gen. ad lit.‚ as far as bestiarum. Cf. Con. Jul. 423: Erat serpens, etc. Sermo 46:12, Erat ibi serpens sapientior omnibus bestiis. De Gen. ad lit. 11:2 has the pluperf. fecerat, instead of the perfect. Note the comment: plures latini codices habent “sapi- mitissimus? non proprio, etc. 2. Cf. Sermo 15329, evidently an adaptation. 3. Cf. Sermo 15319. 4. De Gen. adlit. 11:30 reads dixit ergo. Cf. De cantico novo 8, non morte morieris, eritis sicut dii. 5. De Gen. ad lit. 11:30, Sicut dii, cognoscentes, etc. De Gen. con. Man. 2:26 reads quoniam instead of quia, and ederitis for manducaveritis, and omits ex illo. There are many adaptations of the verse. Cf. De Fide et Sym. 4, Gustate et eritis tanquam dii. Cf. also De lib. arbitrio 3:243 Sermo 153:9; De Trin. 11:5. 6. De Gen. ad lit. 11:30, Vidit bonum ad escam et decorum ad aspectum. Ibid. 11:31 has ergo ederunt, instead of et ederunt. De Gen. con. Man. 2:15 has ad escam instead of in eseam. De civ. 14: 17, Vidit mulier quia bonum lignum in escam et quia placet oeulis ad videndum. Cf. Sermo 151 : 5, Quia placeret ocutis ad videndum. 7. De Gen. ad lit. 11:31 has cognoverunt instead of agnoverunt. De civ. 14:17 follows De Gen. ad lit. 11:1‚ but later in the same chapter has the reading cognoverunt. Cf. Loc. 119. Sermo 151: 5 has Consuerunt folia ficulnea et fecerunt sibi succine- toria. Cf. De Nupt. et Con. 125. 8. De Gen. ad lit. 11:33 reads ambulantis, and ligno quod est in paradiso. Cf. Epist. 148. 10. De Gen. ad lit. 11:34 omits deambulantis. Cf. Con. Jul. 4:16. 11. De Gen. con. Man. 2:16 reads quod nudus esses; and dixerim . . . . ne manducares. Oper. Imper. con.
